  &lt;div class="authors-names"&gt;
    &lt;span class="author-chip"&gt;&lt;span class="author-dot"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;Hasnat&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;span class="author-chip"&gt;&lt;span class="author-dot"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;Bakdaulet&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="authors-meta"&gt;Boston University · MS Applied Business Analytics&lt;/div&gt;




Six views, one question


Where AI actually pays — and where it doesn’t


The “AI premium” is real, but it’s not evenly distributed. Some software skills, work modes, career stages, and states see double-digit pay bumps; others see the opposite. Each chart below is interactive — hover for exact figures.




&lt;div class="viz-header"&gt;
  &lt;div class="viz-number"&gt;01&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div&gt;
    &lt;div class="viz-eyebrow"&gt;Software-skill analysis&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;h3 class="viz-headline"&gt;Java leads the listed software skills, with SQL split sharply by label&lt;/h3&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="viz-explanation"&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
    Java postings show the highest average salary in this table at &lt;strong&gt;$137.2K&lt;/strong&gt;, followed by Sql at
    &lt;strong&gt;$123.8K&lt;/strong&gt; and .NET at &lt;strong&gt;$121.3K&lt;/strong&gt;. Python sits near the middle of the group, while
    the uppercase SQL category is the lowest at &lt;strong&gt;$103.8K&lt;/strong&gt;.
  &lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
    The gap suggests skill labels are picking up different role mixes, not just different tools. Backend and
    platform-oriented software skills cluster higher, while broader database-language postings appear more mixed
    in seniority and function.
  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="viz-body"&gt;
  &lt;div style="font-size:13px; color:var(--slate); margin-bottom:4px;"&gt;Average posted salary by software skill&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div style="font-size:12px; color:var(--slate); margin-bottom:12px;"&gt;Lightcast US job postings, May-Sep 2024&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div style="position:relative; width:100%; height:360px;"&gt;
    &lt;canvas id="softwareSkillSalary" role="img" aria-label="Horizontal bar chart of average salary by software skill."&gt;&lt;/canvas&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div style="font-size:11px; color:var(--slate); margin-top:10px; line-height:1.5;"&gt;
    Salaries are averages from the provided table. Categories are kept exactly as supplied, including separate Sql and SQL labels.
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;div class="viz-header"&gt;
  &lt;div class="viz-number"&gt;02&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div&gt;
    &lt;div class="viz-eyebrow"&gt;Remote-work analysis&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;h3 class="viz-headline"&gt;Remote roles edge out onsite roles by roughly $15.8K on average&lt;/h3&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="viz-explanation"&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
    Fully remote postings average &lt;strong&gt;$116.5K&lt;/strong&gt;, slightly ahead of postings with no remote designation
    and hybrid remote roles. Not remote postings average &lt;strong&gt;$100.7K&lt;/strong&gt;, making them the clear low point
    in this table.
  &lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
    The result lines up with the idea that remote-friendly roles are often more specialized or compete in broader
    labor markets, while onsite roles can reflect more local pay bands and a wider range of job families.
  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="viz-body"&gt;
  &lt;div style="font-size:13px; color:var(--slate); margin-bottom:4px;"&gt;Average posted salary by remote status&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div style="font-size:12px; color:var(--slate); margin-bottom:12px;"&gt;Lightcast US job postings, May-Sep 2024&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div style="position:relative; width:100%; height:340px;"&gt;
    &lt;canvas id="remoteSalary" role="img" aria-label="Bar chart of average salary by remote status."&gt;&lt;/canvas&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div style="font-size:11px; color:var(--slate); margin-top:10px; line-height:1.5;"&gt;
    [None] is retained as a separate category because the posting did not specify a remote-status label in the provided table.
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;div class="viz-header"&gt;
  &lt;div class="viz-number"&gt;03&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div&gt;
    &lt;div class="viz-eyebrow"&gt;State salary analysis&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;h3 class="viz-headline"&gt;Connecticut, New Jersey, and Arkansas top the salary ranking&lt;/h3&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="viz-explanation"&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
    The top three states are tightly packed: Connecticut averages &lt;strong&gt;$124.9K&lt;/strong&gt;, New Jersey
    &lt;strong&gt;$122.9K&lt;/strong&gt;, and Arkansas &lt;strong&gt;$122.2K&lt;/strong&gt;. California appears sixth at
    &lt;strong&gt;$120.8K&lt;/strong&gt;, close to Virginia, Vermont, Montana, and Illinois.
  &lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
    The spread across the top ten is relatively narrow, about &lt;strong&gt;$6.3K&lt;/strong&gt; from Connecticut to
    Washington, D.C., suggesting the highest-paying geographies are clustered more tightly than the skill-level
    salary gaps.
  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="viz-body"&gt;
  &lt;div style="font-size:13px; color:var(--slate); margin-bottom:4px;"&gt;Top 10 states by average posted salary&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div style="font-size:12px; color:var(--slate); margin-bottom:12px;"&gt;Lightcast US job postings, May-Sep 2024&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div style="position:relative; width:100%; height:480px;"&gt;
    &lt;canvas id="topStateSalary" role="img" aria-label="Horizontal bar chart of the top ten states by average salary."&gt;&lt;/canvas&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div style="font-size:11px; color:var(--slate); margin-top:10px; line-height:1.5;"&gt;
    Values are average posted salaries from the provided table. Washington, D.C. is shown with its full district label in the tooltip.
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;div class="viz-header"&gt;
  &lt;div class="viz-number"&gt;04&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div&gt;
    &lt;div class="viz-eyebrow"&gt;Skill-level analysis&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;h3 class="viz-headline"&gt;Generative AI commands a 49% premium — Excel pays 26% less&lt;/h3&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="viz-explanation"&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
    At the top of the salary ladder sit the skills that &lt;strong&gt;build&lt;/strong&gt; AI systems — Generative AI (+49%),
    Kubernetes (+34%), Docker (+29%), and AWS (+27%). At the bottom sit the tools that &lt;strong&gt;consume&lt;/strong&gt;
    their outputs — Excel (-26%), Power BI (-17%), and Tableau (-16%) all post salaries well below market median.
  &lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
    The takeaway: &lt;strong&gt;employers are paying steep premiums for AI infrastructure and ML engineering skills&lt;/strong&gt;,
    while traditional analyst tooling has become commoditized. This is association, not causation — but the gap
    is striking and consistent across thousands of postings.
  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="viz-body"&gt;
  &lt;div style="font-size:13px; color:var(--slate); margin-bottom:4px;"&gt;Median salary of postings mentioning each skill, vs. postings that don't&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div style="font-size:12px; color:var(--slate); margin-bottom:12px;"&gt;Lightcast US job postings, May-Sep 2024 · n = 29,798 full-time postings with salary&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div style="display:flex; gap:16px; margin-bottom:8px; font-size:12px; color:var(--navy-3);"&gt;
    &lt;span style="display:flex; align-items:center; gap:6px;"&gt;&lt;span style="width:10px; height:10px; border-radius:2px; background:#1D9E75;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;Pays above market&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;span style="display:flex; align-items:center; gap:6px;"&gt;&lt;span style="width:10px; height:10px; border-radius:2px; background:#D85A30;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;Pays below market&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div style="position:relative; width:100%; height:760px;"&gt;
    &lt;canvas id="skillPremium" role="img" aria-label="Horizontal bar chart of salary premium by skill."&gt;&lt;/canvas&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div style="font-size:11px; color:var(--slate); margin-top:8px; line-height:1.5;"&gt;
    Read as association, not causation: the skill mix on a posting reflects the kind of role being hired for.
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;div class="viz-header"&gt;
  &lt;div class="viz-number"&gt;05&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div&gt;
    &lt;div class="viz-eyebrow"&gt;Experience-level analysis&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;h3 class="viz-headline"&gt;The AI premium is largest for entry-level — and disappears at the top&lt;/h3&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="viz-explanation"&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
    For entry-level workers (0-2 years), AI postings pay &lt;strong&gt;19.5% more&lt;/strong&gt; than non-AI peers — a $15K bump
    on a median ~$80K base. The gap shrinks to roughly 10% for mid- and senior-level roles, then collapses to essentially
    zero at lead/principal (9+ years).
  &lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
    The pattern suggests AI is currently a &lt;strong&gt;ladder for early-career workers&lt;/strong&gt;, not a multiplier at
    the top. Once you're senior enough, leadership and domain expertise dominate compensation, and the AI label
    no longer adds a separate premium.
  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="viz-body"&gt;
  &lt;div style="font-size:12px; color:var(--slate); margin-bottom:14px;"&gt;
    Median posted salary by minimum-years-experience bucket · Lightcast US, May-Sep 2024 · n = 23,116 postings with experience specified
  &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div style="position:relative; width:100%; height:380px;"&gt;
    &lt;canvas id="expChart" role="img" aria-label="Grouped bar chart of median salary by experience level."&gt;&lt;/canvas&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div style="font-size:11px; color:var(--slate); margin-top:10px; line-height:1.5;"&gt;
    AI postings command a $15K bump for entry-level roles but the gap closes by senior level and inverts slightly
    at lead/principal.
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;


&lt;div class="viz-header"&gt;
  &lt;div class="viz-number"&gt;06&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div&gt;
    &lt;div class="viz-eyebrow"&gt;Geographic analysis&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;h3 class="viz-headline"&gt;Where the AI premium is biggest — not always where you'd guess&lt;/h3&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="viz-explanation"&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
    Among major tech states, &lt;strong&gt;Washington (+33%)&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;California (+20%)&lt;/strong&gt; show the
    steepest AI premiums — consistent with cloud and AI hyperscalers concentrated there. Smaller-volume states
    like Rhode Island and South Carolina top the chart, but with thin samples, treat as directional.
  &lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
    &lt;strong&gt;Kentucky inverts the pattern&lt;/strong&gt; with a -17% premium: its AI postings skew toward lower-paying
    analyst work rather than ML engineering.
  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="viz-body"&gt;
  &lt;div style="font-size:12px; color:var(--slate); margin-bottom:14px;"&gt;
    AI vs non-AI median salary gap, states with &gt;=200 postings · Lightcast US, May-Sep 2024
  &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div style="position:relative; width:100%; height:460px;"&gt;
    &lt;canvas id="stateChart" role="img" aria-label="Horizontal bar chart of AI premium by state."&gt;&lt;/canvas&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div style="font-size:11px; color:var(--slate); margin-top:10px; line-height:1.5;"&gt;
    Among major tech states, Washington (+33%) and California (+20%) show the steepest premiums.
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;


At a glance


The headline numbers


&lt;div class="insight-card"&gt;
  &lt;div class="insight-stat"&gt;$137K&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div class="insight-label"&gt;Average salary for Java postings — highest among the provided software skills&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="insight-card"&gt;
  &lt;div class="insight-stat"&gt;$116K&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div class="insight-label"&gt;Average salary for remote postings — roughly $15.8K above not remote roles&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="insight-card"&gt;
  &lt;div class="insight-stat"&gt;$125K&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;div class="insight-label"&gt;Average salary in Connecticut — highest among the provided top states&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
